{{出典の明記|date=2020年4月}}
{{神社
 | 名称=Mita Hachiman Shrine
 | 画像=[[File:Mita-Hachiman-jinja_inner_shrine.JPG|250px]]<br />Haiden<br />{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|marker=religious-shinto|zoom=13|frame-align=center|frame-width=250}}
 | 所在地={{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|qid=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}{{ill|lt=Minato, Tokyo|Q190088|qid=Q190088|lt=Minato|1=Minato, Tokyo}}{{ill|lt=Mita (Minato, Tokyo)|Q3317048|qid=Q3317048|lt=Mita|1=Mita, Minato, Tokyo}}3-7-16{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}
 | 位置={{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|35|38|35.3|N|139|44|29|E|scale:20000}}
 | 祭神={{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q317997|lt=Hondawake-no-Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin|qid=Q317997}}<br />{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane|qid=Q2564508}}<br />{{ill|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668|qid=Q1073668|1=Takenouchi no Sukune}}-no-Mikoto{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}
 | 社格={{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}{{sfn|東京都神社庁}} / former {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}
 | 創建={{ill|lt=Wadō|Q1373026|qid=Q1373026|1=Wadō (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=709|Q23514|qid=Q23514|1=709}}){{sfn|東京都神社庁}}
 | 例祭={{ill|lt=August 15|Q2774|qid=Q2774|1=August 15}}
 | 地図= {{Location map|Tokyo city|label=Mita<br />Hachiman Shrine|position=top|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
}}

'''Mita Hachiman Shrine''' (みたはちまんじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Mita (Minato, Tokyo)|Q3317048|qid=Q3317048|lt=Mita|1=Mita, Minato, Tokyo}}, {{ill|lt=Minato, Tokyo|Q190088|qid=Q190088|lt=Minato|1=Minato, Tokyo}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|qid=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}.

Its principal deity is {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|qid=Q317997|lt=Hondawake-no-Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}} (Hachiman deity), with {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane|Q2564508|qid=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}} and {{ill|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune|Q1073668|qid=Q1073668|lt=Takenouchi no Sukune-no-Mikoto|1=Takenouchi no Sukune}} as associated deities.

It stands on a slope facing the sea side. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, the {{ill|lt=Tōkaidō|Q1196306|qid=Q1196306|1=Tōkaidō (region)}} ran right in front, and beyond it opened the shore of {{ill|lt=Edo Bay|Q11551101|qid=Q11551101|1=Edo Bay}}, likely giving scenic views. This changed when reclamation of {{ill|lt=Shibaura|Q13489497|qid=Q13489497|1=Shibaura}} began in the Meiji 40s. Tree pruning around the shrine is kept minimal, leaving a dim and quiet atmosphere. On the rear high ground is adjacent {{ill|lt=Kamezuka Park|Q458122|qid=Q458122|1=Kamezuka Park}}.

In {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 21, to commemorate 1300 years of enshrinement, a regular periodic grand festival was held on August 1 and a mikoshi procession on August 2.

===History===
In {{ill|lt=Wadō|Q1373026|qid=Q1373026|1=Wadō (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=709|Q23514|qid=Q23514|1=709}}), it began as a shrine of protection for the eastern provinces, enshrined at Makioka in Musashi. In {{ill|lt=Kankō|Q2736722|qid=Q2736722|1=Kankō}} 7 ({{ill|lt=1011|Q19238|qid=Q19238|1=1011}}), it was moved to Kubo-Mita, Mita-gō, Musashi, and revered as clan shrine of the Watanabe branch of {{ill|lt=Saga Genji|Q11477318|qid=Q11477318|1=Saga Genji}}. In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}' it is recorded as "Hieda Shrine" in Ebara District, Musashi. (The "Engishiki Hieda Shrine" also has other candidate shrines, including {{ill|lt=Hieda Shrine|Q11596288|qid=Q11596288|1=Hieta Shrine}} in Kamata, {{ill|lt=Ōta|Q217234|qid=Q217234|1=Ōta, Tokyo}}, and {{ill|lt=Rokugō Shrine|Q17215324|qid=Q17215324|1=Rokugō Shrine}} in Higashi-Rokugō.)

When {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|Q171977|qid=Q171977|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} entered Edo Castle, an auspicious sign was said to have occurred, and he opened and developed the coast of Kami-Takanawa village (Ebara District) at the current site, building shrine structures there. Relocation was carried out in August {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1662|Q7574|qid=Q7574|1=1662}}). However, a great fire in February Kanbun 8 burned all shrine buildings, and a temporary shrine was placed at Yakushi-ji on {{ill|lt=Isarago-zaka|Q11379690|qid=Q11379690|1=Isarago-zaka}}. Shrine buildings were rebuilt and relocated again in August Kanbun 12.

In {{ill|lt=Keiō|Q776775|qid=Q776775|1=Keiō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1865|Q7708|qid=Q7708|1=1865}}), the {{ill|lt=Jingikan (Meiji)|Q108166762|qid=Q108166762|lt=Jingikan|1=Jingi-kan}} renamed it "Hieda Shrine" as in Engishiki; in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1874|Q7761|qid=Q7761|1=1874}}) it was renamed "Mita Hachiman Shrine" and ranked gōsha; in {{ill|lt=1897|Q7847|qid=Q7847|1=1897}} (Meiji 30) it reverted to '''Mita Hachiman Shrine'''{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}. Shrine buildings from Kanbun 12 were burned in the 1945 Tokyo air raids and rebuilt postwar in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 29.

===Structures===
* Shrine complex - honden, heiden, haiden
* Precinct shrines - Gokō Inari Shrine, Ontake Shrine
* Precinct land - 2,975.9 m²
* Precinct buildings - kaguraden, temizuya, shamusho

